In any of the embodiments of FIGS. 21-28, the insert (both removable and non-removable) may have any one or more of the following attributes:


a durometer between about 40 A and about 70 A, between about 45 A to about 65 A, between about 50 A to about 60 A, between about 40 A to about 60 A, between about 50 A to about 70 A, etc.;

a volume of less than about 10%, less than about 8%, less than about 6%, less than about 5%, less than about 2%, less than about 1%, between about 0.25% to about 1%, between about 1% and about 10%, between about 0.5% to about 1%, between about 0.5% to about 5%, etc. of a volume defined by the liquid retention compartment of the outer shell. For example, a volume of the insert may include a net volume such that the volume does not include any holes in the material of the insert or any aperture(s) defined by the insert. A gross volume of the insert includes all holes and/or apertures defined by the insert;

formed of or includes a mesh material comprising one or more of: open cell foam, closed cell foam, a stainless-steel mesh, an elastomeric waffle, a polyurethane mesh, a silicone mesh, a thermoelastic mesh, or a combination thereof;

prevents or reduces wave propagation through the liquid;

reduces or dissipates turbulence kinetic energy of the liquid;

formed of or includes a compressible mesh material;

an uncompressed state 400, as shown in FIG. 29, when removed from the outer shell and a compressed state 450, as shown in FIG. 30, when positioned in the outer shell;

a diameter 420 of a compressed state 450 of the insert 402 that is less than or equal to a smallest diameter of the liquid retention compartment of the outer shell, as shown in FIG. 30. For example, a diameter 420 of the compressed state 450 may be about 0.5 inches; about 0.25 inches to about 0.75 inches; about 0.5 inches to about one inch; etc. A diameter 410 of the uncompressed state 400 of the insert 402 may be substantially equal to a diameter of a liquid containing compartment, for example about 2 inches to about 5 inches; about 2.5 inches to about 4 inches; about 2.5 inches to about 3.5 inches; about 3 inches; etc., as shown in FIG. 29. In some embodiments, the compressed state 450 represents a semi-compressed state such that the insert 402 is maximally or fully compressed for insertion into the outer shell, but then partially or incrementally expands to fill the liquid retention compartment of the outer shell. In some embodiments, a diameter 420 of the compressed state 450 and/or a diameter 410 of in the uncompressed state 400 represents a maximum diameter of that state. In other embodiments, a diameter 420 of the compressed state 450 and/or a diameter 410 of in the uncompressed state 400 represents a minimum diameter of that state or an average diameter of that state. Although the embodiments in FIGS. 29-30 show an insert that is shaped similarly to an outer shell into which it is placed, one of skill in the art will recognize that any shape of insert is contemplated (e.g., cylindrical, rectangular, etc.);

a diameter 420 of a compressed state 450 of the insert 402 is about 2X to about 10X; about 2X to about 8X; about 4X to about 6X; about 5X to about 7X; etc. less than a diameter 410 of the uncompressed state 400 of the insert 402;

formed of or includes an antimicrobial material;

washable, for example in a washing machine, by hand, in a dishwasher, or otherwise; or

a combination thereof.
